Anxiety disorders, mood disorders, and drug use disorders are the most common mental disorders. The most frequent mental illnesses are anxiety disorders, such as generalized anxiety disorder and panic disorder. They impact around 20% of the world's population. Mood disorders, such as major depressive disorder and bipolar disorder, are very common, affecting around 10% of the worldwide population. Substance use disorders, such as alcohol and drug addiction, impact around 5% of the worldwide population. The prevalence of mental diseases varies according to numerous variables, including age, gender, and geographic region. Depression, for example, is more frequent in women than in males, and the incidence of anxiety disorders is greater in developed nations than in developing ones. The incidence of psychiatric diseases suggests a complex interaction of genetic, environmental, and psychological variables that contribute to the development of these disorders. Multiple genetic and environmental variables, such as stress, trauma, and life events, are believed to affect these illnesses. Furthermore, certain illnesses may have distinct underlying brain pathways that influence their occurrence and appearance. In summary, anxiety disorders, mood disorders, and drug use disorders are the most frequent mental illnesses, with anxiety disorders being the most common. The frequency of mental diseases varies based on a number of characteristics, including age, gender, and geographic region. Because of the great occurrence of these illnesses, it is likely that they are impacted by a complex interaction of hereditary, environmental, and psychological variables, as well as having various underlying brain processes. 